# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crossfit-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The **2007 CrossFit Games** were the inaugural CrossFit Games, which were held on June 30 and July 1, 2007, on a ranch in Aromas, California.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] There was no qualification process for the first Games, and around 70 athletes turned up to participate in the Games, along with around 150 spectators.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] There were three events, the first one selected at random on the day.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The men's individual competition was won by James Fitzgerald, the women's individual by Jolie Gentry.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The Affiliate Cup was awarded to CrossFit Santa Cruz for the best combined team members' individual scores.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] From its inception, the CrossFit Games have awarded an equal sum in prize money to both the male and female winners of the individual competitions, which in the first year was $500.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] In early 2007, the then director of training of CrossFit Dave Castro invited CrossFit founder Greg Glassman to his family ranch in Aromas, California.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] Glassman liked the place, and suggested holding a "Woodstock of Fitness" at the ranch for the CrossFit community.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] After some discussion, they decided to hold CrossFit events at the ranch, where participants can camp and enjoy themselves.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The first Games held therefore had the feel of a backyard barbecue with a few sporting events thrown in.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] In July 2007, the first CrossFit Games took place at the ranch, with Castro serving as the Games director.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The inaugural Games consisted of three events.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The first two events were contested on Day 1, and the final event on Day 2.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The first event was determined on the day by drawing colored balls at random from a hopper (using a peanut roaster), as the founder of CrossFit Greg Glassman believed that the fittest athletes should be able to handle any workout given.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The competitors were scored in each event according to their ranking, and after three events, the competitor with the highest score was crowned the winner.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] There were no separate team events, and the team winner was determined by combining the individual scores of the top two men and top two women of the affiliate in individual events.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] The Affiliate Cup was awarded to the winning team.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] Hopper WOD – 1,000 meters on a Concept-2 rowing machine, followed by 5 rounds of 25 pullups and 7 push jerks.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] Push jerk barbell weight was 135 lb (61 kg) for the men and 95 lb (43 kg) for the women.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] Brett Marshall won the event for the men, Jolie Gentry for the women.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] Trail run – Run of approximately 5 kilometres (3 miles) in length over steep hilly terrain.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] This endurance event was won by Chris Spealler for the men and Kate Hunt for the women.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] CrossFit Total – combined weights of the heaviest back squat, shoulder press, and deadlift that each athlete could successfully complete for a single repetition.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] Athletes may have up to 3 attempts within a 4-minute window for each lift.
[src:crossfit-games/2007-crossfit-games] Connor Banks won for the men's competition, Nicole Dehart for the women's.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The **2008 CrossFit Games** were the second annual CrossFit Games to be held following the inaugural Games in 2007.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The Games were held on July 5–6, 2008, on a ranch in Aromas, California, United States.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] As with the first Games, there was no qualification process for athletes wishing to compete in the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The number of participating athletes was limited to 300 on a first-come first-serve basis, and the number of competition events increased to four.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The men's competition was won by Jason Khalipa, the women's by Caity Matter, and the Affiliate Cup was awarded to CrossFit Oakland.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] Each winner of the individual events won $1,500.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The first documentary film of the Games, *Every Second Counts*, was made for this year's Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The first three events for the second CrossFit Games took place on Saturday July 5, 2008, and the final event was held the following day.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The winners were determined by the lowest cumulative time taken to complete the four events.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The Affiliate Cup was awarded to the affiliate with lowest combined time for its top two men and top two women.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The scoring format for the 2008 games is reflected in the title of the documentary film made of this year's Games, *Every Second Counts*.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] Five rounds of five deadlifts and ten burpees.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The weight for the deadlifts was 275 pounds (125 kilograms) for the men and 185 pounds (84 kilograms) for the women.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] Matt Chan and Libby Dibiase won their respective men's and women's Deadlift/Burpee event.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] A steep trail run over rough terrain approximately 750 meters (2,460 feet) in length.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] Eric O'Connor won the men's Hill Run, Aqueelah Tillman won the women's.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The Squat Grace event comprised thirty squat clean and jerks.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The weights used were 155 pounds (70 kilograms) for the men and 100 pounds (45 kilograms) for the women.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] The participant's starts were staggered so that the competitors set off with the time differentials of their previous days combined score.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] This allowed the spectators to see who the overall winners were since they would finish the event first.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] Jason Khalipa had the best cumulative time of 13 minutes 17 seconds over the four men's events.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] Caity Matter won the Squat Grace and was the overall winner with a total time of 19 minutes 10 seconds in the women's competition.
[src:crossfit-games/2008-crossfit-games] CrossFit Oakland won the Affiliate Cup based on the performance of team members in the individual events.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The **2009 CrossFit Games** were the third annual CrossFit Games held on July 10–12, 2009 at a ranch in Aromas, California.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The men's competition, with a field of 74 competitors, was won by Mikko Salo.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The women's, with a field of 72, was won by Tanya Wagner.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The team competition by Northwest CrossFit.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Qualification events called the Regionals were introduced this year to cope with the increasing number of athletes who wanted to participate in the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] 150 athletes qualified for the individual events, while nearly 100 teams participated in the Affiliate Cup which required no qualification.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The Affiliate Cup became an official team competition this year with its own separate team-based events.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Cuts in the number of athletes in the Games were introduced this year to reduce the field during the course of the competition.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Each winner of the individual competitions received a prize of $5,000.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Steroid testing at the Games was introduced for the first time this year.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Spectators at the Games had grown to an expected 2,500.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Due to the increasing number of competitors, qualification events were initiated this year for individual athletes: 17 Regionals were held worldwide so competitors can qualify for the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] This year there was also a "last chance online qualifier" – athletes who missed the Regionals can submit their videoed workouts via email.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Among those who qualified this way was this year's podium finisher, Tommy Hackenbruck.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Special invites were also given to the top 5 men and women from the 2008 Games and the champions of the 2007 Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] No qualification was required for the team events.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The first five events took place Saturday, July 10, 2009, followed by the last three events on Sunday.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] For the first time, the number of athletes was cut during the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] This year the scoring system was changed to points awarded exactly the same as the placing, i.e. one point for first, two for second, etc.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The competitor with the lowest total would be the winner.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Each competitor completed a 7 kilometer hill run.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] During the run, the previous year's champion Jason Khalipa blacked out, collapsing a few times, but recovered enough to complete the race third from last.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Chris Spealler won the men's event, and Sarah Dunsmore won the women's.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] A deadlift ladder – In 30-second intervals each competitor completes one deadlift in increasing 10 pound increments until they are unable to complete the lift or finish the ladder.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The men started at 315 pounds and went up to 505 pounds while the women started at 185 pound and went up to 375 pounds.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Despite collapsing in the first event, Khalipa managed to win the Deadlift event.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] A 170-meter hill sprint while carrying 35-pound sandbags, two bags for men and one for women.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Each competitor completed a 500-meter row on a Concept-2 rowing machine, hammered a stake into the ground (4-foot for men and 3-foot for women), and then finished with another 500-meter row.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] This event consisted of three rounds of 30 wallballs and 30 squat snatches.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Each competitor had to complete as many rounds as possible in 8 minutes with each round consisting of 4 handstand push-ups, 8 kettlebell swings, and 12 GHD sit-ups.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The competitors progressed through this event by completing the required number of repetitions of each movement before moving to the next movement.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The event consisted of 15 cleans, 30 toes-to-bar, 30 box jumps, 15 muscle-ups, 30 dumbbell push press, 30 double-unders, 15 thrusters, 30 pull-ups, 30 burpees, and 300-foot walking lunges with a barbell plate held overhead.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] For the third annual CrossFit Games, the Affiliate Cup was awarded using a separate team based competition instead of awarding it to an affiliate with the top individual competitors.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Teams only had to register in order to compete without the need to qualify prior to the games, and 96 teams competed.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Team workouts consisted of two men and two women and the teams were allowed two substitute competitors on their roster.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Scoring is the same as for the individual events, i.e. lowest points total wins the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The first three events took place on Friday, July 10, 2009, and the final event was on Sunday, July 12, 2009.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] The first movement was 30 wallballs completed relay style by all four competitors.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Then each competitor had to simultaneously complete a 300 meter row on a Concept-2 rowing machine, 30 twenty-four inch box jumps, 30 kettlebell swings, and 30 dumbbell push press or push jerks with one competitor at each station at a time.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Once each competitor had finished all movements the team moved on to the deadlift station where they each had to complete 30 deadlifts in a relay style.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Each competitor completes a 500 meter leg of the run followed by a final 500 meters run by the entire team.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] Maximum weight 3-repetition overhead squat plus maximum repetitions of pull-ups combined over three attempts.
[src:crossfit-games/2009-crossfit-games] A combined chipper style workout consisting of 75 squat cleans, 150 toes-to-bar, 150 box jumps, 75 thrusters, 35 muscle-ups, 150 burpees, 150 double-unders, and 300-foot walking lunges with a 35lb. plate overhead.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The **2010 CrossFit Games** were the fourth CrossFit Games, held on July 16–18, 2010.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] This year's Games were the first to be staged at the Home Depot Center in Carson, California after three years at the ranch in Aromas.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The men's competition was won by Graham Holmberg, the women's by Kristan Clever, and the Team by CrossFit Fort Vancouver.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] This year the qualification was expanded to a two-stage process with the introduction of Sectionals, a precursor to the online CrossFit Open introduced the following year.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] Individual athletes had to compete in local Sectionals to qualify for the Regionals.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] This was also the first time that regional qualifiers were required for all games participants including individuals, affiliate teams, and masters.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The masters competition was introduced this year for male and female participants over the age of 50.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The number of individual athletes are narrowed down to 50 men and 50 women for the finals at the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The number of scored events in the Games was increased to nine spread over three days of competition.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] With sponsorship from Progenex, each individual winner was awarded $25,000.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The 2010 Games featured the debut of Rich Froning Jr., who would go on to win the Games the following four years.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] He had a lead going into the final event of the 2010 Games, but climbed the rope legless when he could use his legs to help with the climb, and ended up 12th in the event, allowing Holmberg to emerge the winner of the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] This year, the Games were streamed live for the first time online.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The qualification process was expanded this season to two stages with the introduction of Sectionals, which were subdivisions of most of the Regional competitions.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] There were 34 Sectionals, and the events were not standardized across these Sanctionals.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The top men and women from the Sectionals were funnelled into the Regionals where they can qualify for the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] An online qualifier was arranged for military personnel who cannot attend the Sectionals.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The number of Regionals was reduced to 13 this year by amalgamating some regions.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The workouts for the Regionals were also not standardized, and each region had their own workouts.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] 50 men and 50 women can qualify for the finals, and these include the top 5 men and women from the 2009 Games and previous champions, but only 45 men and 41 women went on to compete in the individual competitions in this Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] There were 9 scored events held over 3 days at the Games this year.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The scoring was the same as the 2009 CrossFit Games, with the score identical to the placing (i.e. one point for first, two for second, etc.), and the athlete with the lowest total score would win the competition.
[src:crossfit-games/2010-crossfit-games] The field was reduced to 24 athletes after event 3 on Saturday, then to 16 after event 5 on Sunday.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The **2011 CrossFit Games** were a sporting event, the fifth CrossFit Games, held on July 29–31, 2011, at the Home Depot Center in Carson, California.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The winners of the Games were Rich Froning for the men's competition and Annie Thorisdottir for the women, who were both runners-up the previous year.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] CrossFit New England won the team competition.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] 2011 marked the first year the "CrossFit Open" was used as the first part of a two-stage qualification process for the CrossFit Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Online submissions of workout results were invited from competitors worldwide, and over 26,000 participated.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Athletes were then selected to compete in the Regionals, and those who qualified then proceeded to the CrossFit Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] There were 10 events in the Games, including the first swim event which was held outside the main venue for the first time.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Also starting this season, the Games settled on a scoring system of 100 points for the winner of an event, with decreasing number of points for lower-placed athletes, and the one with the most points at the end of the competition would be the champion.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] CrossFit started a 10-year, $150 million, sponsorship and partnership deal with Reebok in 2011, and the prize money for the male and female individual winners of the Games increased substantially to $250,000 this year.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The 2011 Games were also the first to be covered by ESPN, with live coverage streamed through ESPN3 as well as late shows on ESPN2, and the exposure further increased the popularity of subsequent Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] 2011 was the first year the Open was implemented as part of the qualification process in a CrossFit season.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Over 26,000 athletes participated the Open, which took place in six weeks from March 15 to May 1, 2011.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Competing athletes participated in six workouts, with each workout released to be completed weekly.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Athletes can submit their scores online either with video evidence or validation by judges in a CrossFit affiliate.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Annie Thorisdottir and Dan Bailey were the respective female and male individual winners of the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The point system used in both the Open was the same as that used for the Games last year, with points awarded directly corresponding to the rankings (1 point for first, 2 points for second, etc.).
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] For teams, the combined scores of the individuals from a single gym were used to rank a team.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Scoring for the Open stayed the same for all subsequent seasons.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] In each of the 17 regions, 60 individual athletes and 30 teams with the best results proceeded to compete in the Regionals.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The Regionals were held over three days from May 27 to June 19, 2011.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The workouts for the Regionals were standardized this year, and all athletes had to compete in the same six events to determine the qualifiers for the CrossFit Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The scoring system for the Regionals was the same as the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] A minimum work requirement was introduced for a Regional event for the first time.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Failure by an athlete to complete a certain movement, for example, a single handstand push-up in the first event, would result in elimination.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] In each Regional, the competing athletes were first cut to 14 men, 14 women, and 10 team after four events before proceeding to compete in the last two events.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The number of qualifiers for the Games varied for each of the Regional competitions, but no more than three men and three women may qualify from each Regional.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] This is also the last Games where special invites were offered to the top 5 men and women of the preceding Games and winners of earlier Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] A total of 49 male and 47 female qualifiers went on to compete in the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Starting this year, CrossFit awarded prize money to all who qualified from the Regionals to the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The 2011 CrossFit Games featured the first event to be held outside of the main venue, which is the Beach event held on the beach at Santa Monica Pier.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] This was also the first swim event to be introduced at the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] 10 events were held in total, the other 9 events were held at the various stadiums of Home Depot Center.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The number of athletes were cut to 35 men and 35 women after the 6th event, 24 after the 7th, with 12 competing in the final event.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The point system was modified for the Games this year.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Scoring in the team events was the same as for the individuals, but the Friday and Saturday team events were considered qualifiers for the final event on Sunday.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] Only 6 teams may qualify for the final event, where scores were reset.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] The team that won this event were declared the champions.
[src:crossfit-games/2011-crossfit-games] CrossFit New England won the competition, winning $30,000 in prize money.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] The **2012 CrossFit Games** were the sixth edition of the CrossFit Games, held on July 11–15, 2012, at the Home Depot Center in Carson, California, with some events taking place at Camp Pendleton.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] The men's competition was won by Rich Froning Jr., the women's by Annie Thorisdottir, and the Affiliate Cup by Hacks Pack UTE.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] Both Froning and Thorisdottir were repeat champions from the previous year.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] The number of participants increased to 69,000 for this year's Open.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] In this season, the special invites to previous champions were removed and they all had to qualify through the Regionals.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] At the Games, 15 events took place over four days, the most yet for a Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] in this season, 69,000 athletes registered to compete in the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] The Open took place over five weeks (reduced from six in 2011) from February 22 to March 25, 2012, during which a workout was release every week for the athletes to perform, and athletes can then submit their results for each of the 5 workouts before the deadline every week.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] Cash prizes were offered to participants selected for the Spirit of the Open award, as well as individual winners in the Open from this year onward.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] Rich Froning and Kristan Clever were the respective Open male and female individual winners.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] From the Open, 60 men, 60 women and 30 teams of each region with the best results proceeded to compete in 17 Regionals that took place from April 27 to May 27.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] Previous champions also had to compete in the Regionals, but extra qualification places were provided for regions where the champions competed.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] Athletes competed in 6 events in the Regionals – after five events, the field was cut to 18 in each Regional.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] Both the Open and Regionals again used a point system different from the one used in the Games: points were awarded according to the position (1 point for first place, etc.), those with the lowest total points would qualify for the next stage.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] 91 athletes, 46 men and 45 women, went on to compete in the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] The first three event were held at Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton, which were unexpected additions, taking place as they did two days before athletes had expected the Games to start.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] A rest day was introduced after the events at Camp Pendleton before competition resumed at the Home Depot Center in Carson.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] The scoring system was the same as for 2011, with all events scoring 100 points for the winner apart a few events: the Broad Jump, Ball Toss, and Sprint events were scored 50 points.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] The number of athletes was cut to 36 after the Clean Ladder event, 24 after the Chipper, 18 after the Double-banger, 15 after Elizabeth, 12 after Isabel.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] The scoring system for the team events was the same as for 2011, where the Friday and Saturday events were regarded as qualifiers, and the scores were wiped clean for the final events on Sunday.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] Six teams competed in the same final events ("The Girls") as 2011, with the winners crowned the team champions.
[src:crossfit-games/2012-crossfit-games] Unlike previous Games, all six members are required to compete in every events.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] The **2013 CrossFit Games**, the seventh CrossFit Games, were held on July 24–28, 2013, at the StubHub Center in Carson, California.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] The men's competition was won by Rich Froning Jr., the women's by Samantha Briggs, and the Affiliate Cup by Hacks Pack UTE.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] This year 138,000 athletes took part in the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] The cash prize for the individual winners at the Games increased to $275,000.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] This is the first year prize money was also awarded to the top three finishers of each event.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] In this season, 138,000 registered for the Open to compete for a place in the Regionals of the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] The Open was held over five weeks from March 6 to April 7, with 5 workouts released for the athletes to complete, one per week.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] This is the first season where the Open workouts were announced live instead of being pre-recorded.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Rich Froning and Samantha Briggs were the respective male and female individual winners of the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] The number of qualifiers from the Open who can compete in the Regionals were reduced to 48 men and 48 women per region this year.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Qualifiers from the Open proceeded to take part in 7 events in three days in the Regionals; the 17 Regionals were spread over 4 weekends from May 17 through June 9, 2013.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Six of these Regionals streamed their events live online.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Unlike the preceding season, no athletes were cut during the competition.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Three athletes from each Regionals qualified for the Games, apart from the Canadian Regionals (two each), and Asia, Africa and Latin America (one each).
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] The scoring system for the Open and Regionals is the same as previous years (one point for first, two for second, etc.).
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] As with the 2012 season, extra places were given to Regionals where previous champions competed and qualified for the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] CrossFit Games also exercised its right to offer a place in the Games to athletes who failed to qualify, which this year included past champion Kristan Clever.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] 47 men, 44 women, 43 teams were invited to the 2013 Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] 46 men and 44 women turned up at the 2013 Games to compete.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] The scoring system used was the same as the 2012 Games', and all events were scored a maximum of 100 points.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] 10 rounds of: swim 25-yard swim, 3 bar muscle-ups, swim 25-yard swim.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] As with the Pendleton events in 2012, The Pool was a surprise addition to the Games, starting on Wednesday two days before the official start date.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] It was held at the Woollett Aquatic Center, and was the first swimming event to be held at the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Jordan Troyan won the men's event, and Michelle Letendre the women's.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Complete 2000 meters on an indoor rower as fast as possible, and then continue rowing for an additional 19,097 m (half marathon distance) as fast as possible.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Jason Khalipa won both the rowing events for the men, Samantha Briggs was first for both the women (Kaleena Ladeairous was joint first for the first row).
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Alternating sets of thrusters (front squat + push press) and no-legs rope climbs with decreasing repetitions each set.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Thruster weight: 95 lb for men and 65 lb for women; rope climb height: 15 ft.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Unlike 2011 and 2012 when scores were wiped clean before the final day, scores for all events counted going into the Sunday events.
[src:crossfit-games/2013-crossfit-games] Most events were scored a maximum of 100, except for a few which were scored 50 points (Iditarod 1/2/3).
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The **CrossFit Games** is an annual athletic competition owned and operated by CrossFit, LLC.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Athletes compete in a series of events at the Games, which may be various standard CrossFit workouts consisting of metabolic conditioning exercises, weightlifting, and gymnastics movements, as well as a range of activities from other sports such as swimming, road cycling and strongman.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The events generally are not revealed before the Games, can include unexpected elements to challenge the athletes' readiness to compete, and they are designed to test the athletes' fitness using CrossFit's own criteria.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The competition started in 2007 and has been held every year since, normally in the summer.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] It was held in the Dickies Arena in Fort Worth, Texas in 2024.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Games were sponsored by Reebok from 2011 to 2020, and by Nobull from 2021 to 2023.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The CrossFit Games season consists of four stages; the first qualification stage, the Open, is billed as the largest participatory sporting event in the world, with over 415,000 athletes signing up to compete in 2018.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The number of participants are reduced in further qualification events to 30 men, 30 women and 20 teams, who go on to compete at the CrossFit Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] A few athletes have dominated in the Games' history; they are Rich Froning (four wins) and Mat Fraser (five wins) in the men's competition, and Tia-Clair Toomey (eight wins) in the women's.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The CrossFit Games has its origin in early 2007 when the then director of training of CrossFit Dave Castro invited CrossFit founder Greg Glassman to his family ranch in Aromas, California, and Glassman suggested holding a "Woodstock of Fitness" at the ranch for the CrossFit community.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In July 2007, the inaugural CrossFit Games took place at the ranch in Aromas.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The first Games had the feel of a backyard barbecue with a few sporting events thrown in, and around 70 athletes and 150 spectators turned up for the competition.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] For the first two years of competition, participation was open to anyone who showed up at Aromas.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The athletes with the best individual combined score in a series of events would be crowned the winners, and an Affiliate Cup was also awarded to the group from one CrossFit gym that had the best combined individual standings.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The number of participants increased rapidly in the following years, and in 2009, a qualification stage called the Regionals was introduced to select the best competitors for the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The CrossFit Games also added a separate set of team-based events for the Affiliate Cup, marking the first use of a designated Team Division, competed by teams of four (two men and two women).
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] This year, spectators at the Games had grown to an expected 2,500.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Interest and attendance at the Games outgrew the ranch in Aromas, and in 2010 the Games venue was moved to the Home Depot Center in Carson, California.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Participation in the event continued to grow, and the qualification for the 2010 Games was adjusted to include multiple Sectionals, a series of events open to all athletes who wanted to qualify for one of the 17 Regionals.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The 17 regions divided Canada and the United States into 12 regions, with the remaining regions roughly corresponding to the five other populated continents.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Games also expanded the Team Division to groups of six athletes and added a Masters Division for individual men and women aged 55 and up.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2011, the open participation Sectionals were replaced by an online qualification called the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In the first year of the Open, 26,000 athletes signed up to compete.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Participation in the Open steadily increased, rising from 69,000 in 2012 to 209,585 in 2014.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Open has since been described as the largest participatory sporting event in the world, reaching a peak of 415,000 participants in 2018.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The number of registered athletes in the Open declined in the next two years down to 239,106 in 2020, which may be due to changes of the 2019 Games and the scheduling of the 2020 Open, but has steadily increased in the following years, to over 323,000 in 2023.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2015, the qualification format was reorganized from 17 Regionals to eight "Super-Regionals".
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Each Super-Regional included qualifiers from two or three of the previously defined regions, with a total of 40 or 50 athletes participating at each event.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] From these Super-Regionals, 40 men, 40 women, and 40 teams went on to participate at the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Following seven years in Carson, the Games moved to the grounds of the Alliant Energy Center in Madison, Wisconsin, in 2017.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The next year, the qualifying Regionals were once again realigned to reflect the increasing competitiveness and popularity outside of Canada and the U.S.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2018, there were nine Regionals hosted among 18 redefined regions, with Europe increasing to three regions, Central America split from South America, and the elimination of the Northern and Southern California regions.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] CrossFit, Inc. founder Greg Glassman overhauled the format for the 2019 Games, replacing the Regionals with CrossFit-sanctioned international qualifying events called Sanctionals.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] As part of the changes, the 2019 Games athletes can qualify by winning one of the Sanctionals, or were the top athlete from one of the recognized countries in the CrossFit Open, or a top-20 overall finisher in the CrossFit Open, or by being one of the up to four at-large athletes chosen by CrossFit.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Teams also no longer needed to be created from one CrossFit-affiliated gym and could be formed from any group of four competitors.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2020, the qualifying events proceeded as scheduled until March 2020 when the COVID-19 pandemic caused events to be cancelled amid social distancing requirements and travel restrictions.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Games format was altered, and 30 men and 30 women were invited to compete in an online-only first stage with the top five qualifying for the final stage.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] As no spectators were allowed at any venue during the pandemic, the final stage was hosted at its original location at the CrossFit Ranch in Aromas.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] There were no teams, masters, or teens events.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2021, the qualification format was adjusted with the introduction of a new online Quarterfinal stage.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] However, the Games also removed the national champion so as to have a smaller field of invitees to the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Ten Semi-finals that are a mix of the Regionals and Sanctionals were also introduced, as well as a final last-chance online qualifier for semi-final athletes who narrowly missed Games qualification.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Games also returned the team format to affiliate-based qualification, and added a new adaptive athlete division.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In January 2022, CrossFit CEO Eric Roza dismissed CrossFit Games' director Dave Castro after 15 years of programming the event, replacing him with Justin Bergh as general manager of sport and Adrian Bozman as director of competition.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Castro later returned as leader of the sport team in 2023.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] A worldwide ranking of athletes was introduced for the 2023 Games based on the performance of the athletes in all stages of the previous two Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] This ranking system would be used to determine any additional qualifying spots for the CrossFit Games in a revamped qualification process.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] For the 2024 season, the CrossFit Games were held in the Dickies Arena in Fort Worth, Texas after 6 years in Madison, Wisconsin.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In that season the Games focused on the individual and team divisions, with all the other divisions split off into their own separate competitions.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Games, however, were marred by the death of the Serbian athlete Lazar Đukić, who drowned in the first event, which led to the withdrawal of a number of athletes, including both 2023 champions Laura Horvath and Jeffrey Adler.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] After only a year in Fort Worth, the Games were moved to Albany, New York for the 2025 season.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Other changes were made this season, including the removal of the quarterfinals, and only 30 men, 30 women and 20 teams can qualify for the Games. in 2026, for the 20th anniversary, the Games return to California where the competition will be held at the SAP Center in San Jose.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Participation and sponsorship have grown rapidly since the inception of the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Games has always awarded an equal sum in prize money to the male and female individual winners, starting with $500 at the inaugural Games, increasing to $300,000 in 2019.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The prize purse of the 2010 Games was sponsored by Progenex that provided $25,000 for the winners.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The following year saw the largest jump in prize money when Reebok sponsored its first Games, and the prize money for first place in 2011 increased to $250,000.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The total prize payout in 2016 was $2,200,000, rising to 3 million in 2020.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The prize payout increased again in 2021 when NoBull became the title sponsor of the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] There was no title sponsor for the 2024 CrossFit Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The CrossFit Games is the culmination of the CrossFit season that starts with the qualification stage.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In the first two CrossFit Games, no qualification for competitors was necessary; athletes who wanted to participate in the Games could register and turn up on the day to compete.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] However, with an increasing number of participants, a qualification process, the Regionals, was initiated in 2009 to winnow down the number of athletes who could take part in the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] This was further expanded into a two-stage process in 2010 with the introduction of Sectionals where competitors were first selected to compete in the Regionals.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Sectionals became the Open the following year, and between 2011 and 2018, all athletes had to go through the same two-stage qualification process, the Open and Regionals, apart from a few who received special invites in some years.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In the 2019 CrossFit Games, the qualification process was modified, and competitors had three separate ways to qualify: the Open, sanctioned events, and by invitation.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2021, the Open once again reverted to its role as the first stage of competition that feeds the subsequent rounds, the Quarterfinals and Semifinals, in an expanded three-stage continent-based qualification system.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Open was introduced in 2011 and participation is open to anyone over a certain age limit (14 since 2015) and at any skill level.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Open is held over a number of weeks, and a series of workouts are released weekly for competitors to complete.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Each week competitors perform the workouts and submit their scores online before a specified time supported by either videos of their workouts or validations by a CrossFit affiliate.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In every event, the competitors are ranked according to their performance with points awarded directly corresponding to their rank (i.e. one point for first, two for second, etc.), and the winner is the one with the lowest cumulative points over the course of the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] From 2011 to 2019, the Open was usually held over five weeks in February and March with a new workout released each week, and athletes had to submit their score for each workout usually four days later.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] For the 2020 season, the Open moved forward to October 2019 as part of the overhaul for Games qualifications so that it took place before any of the sanctioned events.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] It has been moved back to February or March since the 2021 season.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2019, the top athlete from each country (the national champion) and the top 20 overall Open finishers qualified directly to the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] This was also planned for 2020, but the COVID-19 pandemic travel restrictions led to only 20 men and 20 women from the Open being invited to an online competition as the first stage of the Games itself, and no national champion has been invited to the Games since.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2021, the Open reverted to be the starting point of the competition, but the number of weeks was reduced to three with only four workouts held.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Three or four workouts have been held for the Open since 2022.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] For the 2021 Games, the qualification system was again revamped, and a quarterfinal stage was added between the Open and the semifinals.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Participants in the Open were separated on a continental basis, and only the top 10% on each continent can qualify for the quarterfinal.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2024, this was raised to the top 25%.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The quarterfinals start around a week and a half after the Open has finished, and are held online similar to the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The athletes are required to complete five workouts over 3 consecutive days after the workouts have been released.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The quarterfinals were removed in 2025, and athletes moved directly from the Open to the semifinals, but are restored in 2026.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Between 2009 and 2018, competitors qualified for the Games through participation at CrossFit Games regional events around the world.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The top men and women from the Sectional in 2010, and the Open from 2011 to 2018, participated in the Regionals to qualify for the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] There were 17 Regionals most years until 2015, when athletes from the 17 regions (later 18 regions) were funnelled into 8 or 9 Regional competitions.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2011, the events in the Regionals were standardized.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] For the 2019 Games, CrossFit, Inc. discontinued hosting the Regional qualifier and instead sanctioned independent fitness events as qualifiers separate from the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] These events were trademarked as "Sanctionals" by CrossFit, LLC.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Most of the sanctioned events were significant CrossFit competitions already widely participated in by CrossFit Games athletes around the world, such as Wodapalooza and Dubai CrossFit Championship, as well as the newly created Rogue Invitational.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Each sanctioned event had its own rules for participation and separately programmed events.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] If an athlete or team won multiple sanctioned events, the runners-up from the later events would qualify to the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Twenty-eight sanctioned events were announced for the 2020 season, but many of them were cancelled due to the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2021, the revamped semifinals were a mix of the Regionals and Sanctionals, with 10 semifinals scheduled in 6 continents.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] A last-chance online qualifier, last used in 2009, was reintroduced for semifinal athletes who narrowly missed a Games qualification.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2022, CrossFit reintroduced identical workouts but only for two of the semifinal events.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] This is further extended in 2023 when all the workouts for the semifinals would be standardized, but the number of semifinals were reduced to seven, and the last chance qualifier eliminated.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Each region is guaranteed a certain number of qualifiers to the Games, with extra spots allocated to each region using a strength of field calculation based a worldwide ranking system.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2025, the quarterfinals were removed in another revamp, and the top 1% of participating athletes in the individual divisions move directly to take part in in-affiliate semifinals and nine in-person qualifying events.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] From 2009 to 2011, special invites were given to the top 5 men and women from the preceding Games as well as the individual champions of all previous games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The special invites for previous champions were removed in 2012, although CrossFit reserved the right to extend an invitation at any stage of the Games to any athlete, a right it exercised for two athletes in 2013.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2019, the CrossFit Games had the option to invite up to four athletes who did not qualify for the Games in the Open or sanctioned events as an at-large bid.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Athletes at the Games compete in a series of workouts and activities over the course of a few days.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The competition events at the CrossFit Games are not necessarily the same as workouts in a CrossFit gym and can include elements not normally seen in a CrossFit gym.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Athletes are therefore kept in the dark as to exactly what they may face in the Games, and they may learn about the events days, hours, or minutes beforehand, sometimes not knowing the details of the events even after they have started on the event.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] These events test the athletes on what CrossFit defines as the ten fitness domains: "cardiovascular/respiratory endurance, stamina, strength, flexibility, power, speed, coordination, agility, balance, and accuracy", so that the fittest athlete can be determined using CrossFit's own criteria.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The first Games only had 3 events; in the following years, the number of events gradually increased, and the Games now typically have 12–15 events held over a period of three to five days.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Each event is scored individually; since 2011 the scoring system awards 100 points for the winner of every event, with lower-placing athletes receiving fewer points according to a points table.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The athlete with the best combined score across all events is declared the champion and the "Fittest on Earth".
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The events are mostly an assortment of Crossfit workouts comprising exercises in monostructural/metabolic conditioning ("metcon"), weightlifting, and gymnastics, which are the three CrossFit modalities.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The standard CrossFit workouts are usually a combination of movements of different modalities, such as handstand push-up, pull-up, muscle-up, burpee, lunge, box-jump, rope-climb, double under, running, back squat and dumbbell push press.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Each workout may involve a number of rounds and repetitions (reps) of different movements, for example, a workout may have a rep scheme comprising three rounds of 21–15–9 repetitions of each movement.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Workouts with "rounds for time" structure are won by competitors who can finish the rounds of workouts in the fastest time, while workouts in the "as many reps/rounds as possible" (AMRAP) format are won by those who complete the most reps or rounds within a set time.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The workouts may be given specific names, for example, "Grace", "Fran", and "Amanda" from "The Girls" workouts, and "Murph" from the "Heroes" and tribute workouts.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Events titled "Couplet" are composed of two different movements, while "Triplet" events have three.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The "Chipper" events typically involve many different movements performed in sequence, while the "Ladder" events may involve increasing/decreasing number of reps or heavier/lighter weights in each succeeding round.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Games often introduces some additional surprise elements that are not part of the typical CrossFit regimen to the events.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] These include obstacle courses, road cycling, ocean swimming, softball throwing, or ascending a pegboard.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The marquee events at the CrossFit Games are the men's and women's individual competitions.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The first place prize for each paid out $300,000 in 2020, with that amount set to increase to $310,000 in 2021.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Originally, teams were awarded the Affiliate Cup for having the best overall score from the individual athletes that had come from the same CrossFit-affiliated gym.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2009, the Games began having a separate set of events for affiliate teams and consisted of four to six athletes from the same gym.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The next season, the format was finalized to teams of three men and three women.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In the 2018 games, each team was changed to four members, two men and two women.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2019, CrossFit removed the stipulation that team members had to be from the same affiliate.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Teams are subject to a similar qualification process as the individuals.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2021, the Games returned to affiliate-only teams and the Affiliate Cup.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Until 2024, the Games included age-based divisions for younger and older competitors.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Masters divisions were introduced at the 2010 Games for those over 50.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The number of Masters divisions increased in the following years; currently there are seven divisions each for women and men: 35–39, 40–44, 45–49, 50–54, 55–59, 60–64, and 65+.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Divisions for teenagers were introduced in 2015: the age ranges are 14–15 and 16–17, for both boys and girls.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Rather than regional events, masters and teen athletes qualified for the games by a second online competition following the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The top 200 athletes in each division worldwide were invited to compete in this qualifier, of which the top 10 advance to the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Prior to the introduction of these secondary online qualifiers, masters and teens competitors qualified for the Games directly from the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] For the 2024 season, the finals of the Masters and Teens divisions became separated from the CrossFit Games; the Masters competed in the Legends Championship, while the Teens competed in the Pit Teen Throwdown.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The adaptive divisions were introduced in the 2021 CrossFit Open for competitors with physical impairment.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] There are 16 adaptive divisions (eight each for men and women) with no separation by age, but all competitors must be at least 14 years of age.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Three male and three female divisions participated at the Games, while the rest are tested virtually in the semi-finals.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] All stages of the adaptive divisions including the Open became separated from the CrossFit Games in 2024, and adaptive athletes competed in the WheelWOD Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Due to CrossFit's official partnership with Reebok, competitors at the 2015 Games were banned from wearing Nike footwear.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Nike arranged for several trucks to be parked near the main entrance to the arena, which served as mobile billboards with the slogan "Don't ban our shoe, beat our shoe".
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The partnership also prohibits Nike from labeling its *Metcon* shoes as intended for CrossFit – the brand uses the term "high intensity training" instead.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] CrossFit's decision to award winners of the 2016 Games with handguns resulted in widespread criticism from members and sponsors.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Resulting protests forced the temporary closure of two CrossFit locations in New York City.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] On June 9, Glassman resigned as CEO and sold the company by the end of the month, leading to the boycotting athletes returning.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Athletes from Taiwan are required to compete under the People's Republic of China flag, rather than the Republic of China flag.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] *South China Morning Post* reported that athletes have emailed CrossFit HQ, without any feedback.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] At the 2024 CrossFit Games, a competitor from Serbia, Lazar Đukić, died from drowning in the first event that involved an open-water swim.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Criticisms have been voiced on the decision to hold an outdoor run and swim event in the heat of Texas, where the water temperature may be too high to be safe, and on the availability of lifeguards and safety personnel at the event.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Some athletes also criticized the decision to continue with the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The leader of the sport team Dave Castro had falsely claimed before a vote by athletes to continue the competition that the Đukić family wanted the Games to continue as a tribute to Lazar.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Luka Đukić, brother of Lazar and the only family member who was there as a competitor, later revealed he had not agreed to it and that Castro said to him the decision was "not up to you anyways".
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] A number of athletes including both 2023 champions Laura Horvath and Jeffrey Adler chose to withdraw from the competition.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Horvath accused CrossFit to be the one responsible for Đukić's death, she also thought their response to the death "inhumane", and that CrossFit was a corporation whose "basic instinct is survival and profit".
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The Professional Fitness Athletes' Association (PFAA), a group representing the interest of CrossFit athletes, called for transparency on the investigation into the death, the creation of an independent safety team, and the removal of Dave Castro as leader of the sport team.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] CrossFit, however, refused to publish the third-party report on Đukić's death “based on privacy and legal considerations”.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] The rationale for the decision not to publish was described by CrossFit founder Greg Glassman (who is no longer involved in CrossFit) as "bullshit".
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] CrossFit created its own safety advisory board, and kept Castro as leader of the sport team.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] It also established instead its own CrossFit Athlete Council as an alternative to PFAA.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] PFAA expressed its dissatisfaction with CrossFit's response and said that it would support any athlete should they wish to boycott the Games and explore alternative competitive routes.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] A number of prominent athletes, including Patrick Vellner, Laura Horvath, and Annie Thorisdottir, opted not to take part in the 2025 Games season, and affiliates have announced their de-affiliation from CrossFit or non-participation in the Open.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Participation in the 2025 CrossFit Open fell over 30% from nearly 350,000 athletes in 2024 to 234,000.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] More than 1,400 CrossFit gyms also de-affiliated in 2024, 857 of them after the Crossfit Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2011, ESPN began to broadcast the CrossFit Games, with live coverage streamed through ESPN3, and some television coverage on ESPN2.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] As the event grew, ESPN expanded its television coverage; in 2014, the network entered into a multi-year deal to continue broadcasting the CrossFit Games, and coverage expanded to nine-and-a-half hours on ESPN and ESPN2 by 2015.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2017, the event began a new broadcast arrangement with CBS Sports, with television coverage on CBS Sports Network, and a total of 40 hours of digital streaming coverage.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2019, CrossFit experimented with an open-source broadcasting system that allowed various partners to broadcast the Games, but live broadcast resumed on CBS Sports in 2020.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] In 2023, ESPN returned as broadcaster for the Games with live coverage on ESPN, ESPN2 and ESPN+.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] For many years CrossFit had its own media department that was responsible for creating and releasing media content related to the Games, including live streaming of the Games online through Facebook, YouTube and CrossFit websites, and content broadcast on ESPN and CBS.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Events such as the Open workout announcements were broadcast live from 2013 to 2018, and featured two or more past CrossFit Games athletes competing head-to-head immediately following the workout description.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] During the 2018–19 restructuring, CrossFit dissolved its own media crew, relying instead on outside media outlets and production companies for coverage of the sport.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] For the next two years, Rogue Fitness broadcast the coverage of the Open workout announcement with competing athletes performing the workouts, and provided color commentary for the live stream of the Games.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] CrossFit resumed live streaming of its Open announcements in 2021.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] CrossFit's media department also produced a series of documentary films on the Games since 2015, and its former employees continued to produce them independently after the department was dissolved.
[src:crossfit-games/crossfit-games] Josée Sarda originally finished first but was later disqualified for testing positive for banned performance-enhancing substances.
